title: For Sale/Trade:  Smith & Wesson Combat Masterpiece 38 Special - 1951 5 screw frame
postcontent:
This is a S&W Combat Masterpiece revolver that was shipped from the factory in 1951. These are excellent and highly desirable handguns, both from a collecting standpoint and a shooter's perspective.

Essentially, the Combat Masterpiece was the K-38 Masterpiece, but fitted with a 4" barrel and a combat style sight (known as the Baughman Ramp or "Quick Draw" sight, it was designed by an FBI agent, for whom it was named). There is a very slight difference in the frame contour, but essentially the frame of the K-38 Masterpiece and the Combat Masterpiece were the same.

The 5 screw frames, like this one, was discontinued in about 1956. This revolver is in Excellent condition and will carry some collector value and interest. 

I'm testing the waters to see what kind of offers/trades this will bring.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Charter Arms AR-7 Explorer
postcontent:
This is the Charter Arms AR-7. Henry Repeating Arms is the current manufacturer.
  First designed by Armalite in 1959, the venerable AR-7 has been the choice of U.S. Air Force pilots who need a small-caliber rifle they can count on for survival should they have to punch out over a remote area. Over the years, the AR-7's reputation for portability, ease of operation and reliability has carried over to the civilian world as well.
  Today, it's a favorite of bush pilots, backpackers and backcountry adventurers who, like their Air Force counterparts, need a rifle that's easy to carry but has the accuracy to reliably take down small game.
  This innovative, semi-automatic rifle is lightweight (just 2.5 lbs) and highly portable. At just 16 ½" long (when all the components are stowed), it fits easily into the cargo area of a plane or boat or in a backpack. And because it's chambered in .22LR you can carry a large quantity of ammunition, without adding much weight to your gear.
  When disassembled, the pieces fit inside the impact-resistant, water-resistant stock. Assembly is as easy as attaching the receiver to the stock, inserting the barrel and screwing on the barrel nut. In just a few seconds, without the need for any tools, the  AR-7 is ready for action.
  The AR-7 has a sturdy steel barrel covered in aluminum and then coated with Teflon for complete protection against corrosion. Plus, it's engineered for perfect balance and the ability to maintain its tack-driving accuracy, even after thousands of rounds.
  Like the barrel, the receiver is also coated with a layer of waterproof Teflon for superior weatherproofing, waterproof protection, even in harsh salt water environments.
  It is equipped with an adjustable rear peep sight and a blade front sight.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Taurus PT92 AFS 9mm
postcontent:
This LNIB service pistol is the spitting image of the Beretta Model 92FS (with a few improvements) and sells for $100 to $150 less than the glamorous Italian’s price tag.

When Taurus made the first PT-92 in 1980, they didn’t copy or reverse-engineer the Beretta Model 92F as is sometimes believed. Instead, they bought Beretta’s entire Brazilian factory in Sao Paulo with its machinery, parts and plans. They even kept Beretta’s trained workers at their stations. 

Taurus has specially designed a drop hammer forged ordnance grade alloy frame that won't crack or allow the slide to come off.  They’ve also included a three-position frame-mounted ambidextrous safety, which is more secure than a slide mounted safety, and allows for a classic SA "cocked-and-locked" mode, as well as functioning as a DA de-cocking lever. With the 3 dot fixed combat sight model 92 you'll be able to face any situation without compromise.

In all aspects of its fit and machining, the Taurus is every bit as good as the much costlier Beretta Model 92FS it’s patterned after. The Taurus’ metal finish is smooth and even. And Taurus uses a stainless-steel guide rod rather than the Beretta’s plastic rod.

Smooth SA/DA trigger
Built in rail for mounting accessories
Two 17 round mags (Will take 19 round mags, after market Mec-Gar 18 round mags, and Beretta M9 surplus mags)  
All Taurus Firearms Feature A Lifetime Repair Warranty.
